Term Deposit Purchase Prediction¶

Banks usually run some direct marketing campaigns to improve customer subscription of term deposits. The dataset used here is from a direct marketing campaign of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. The objective is to predict whether a given customer has subscribed to a term deposit or not.

This is a supervised classification problem. The dataset is also imbalanced - The number of 'not subscribed' category is very high compared to number of 'not subscribed' category.

Techniques used for handling imbalanced dataset¶

1> Random Under Sampling (RUS)

2> Random Over Sampling (ROS)

3> Under sampling - Tomek Links

4> SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique)

5> NearMiss

6> Penalized SVM

Scoring¶

As dataset is imbalanced, F1-Score is used as it is a more apt scoring method than Accuracy score.

About the dataset

The dataset used here is taken from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/222/bank+marketing. It contains customer and campaign details.

Attributes of data¶

bank client data:

1 - age (numeric)

2 - job : type of job (categorical: "admin.","unknown","unemployed","management","housemaid","entrepreneur","student", "blue-collar","self-employed","retired","technician","services")

3 - marital : marital status (categorical: "married","divorced","single"; note: "divorced" means divorced or widowed)

4 - education (categorical: "unknown","secondary","primary","tertiary")

5 - default: has credit in default? (binary: "yes","no")

6 - balance: average yearly balance, in euros (numeric)

7 - housing: has housing loan? (binary: "yes","no")

8 - loan: has personal loan? (binary: "yes","no")

related with the last contact of the current campaign:

9 - contact: contact communication type (categorical: "unknown","telephone","cellular")

10 - day: last contact day of the month (numeric)

11 - month: last contact month of year (categorical: "jan", "feb", "mar", ..., "nov", "dec")

12 - duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric)

other attributes:

13 - campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)

14 - pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric, -1 means client was not previously contacted)

15 - previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)

16 - poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: "unknown","other","failure","success")

Output variable (desired target):

17 - y - has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: "yes","no")

# Creating 'Age Group' feature
bins = [18, 30, 40, 50, 60, 100]
labels = ['18-30', '31-40', '41-50', '51-60', '61+']
df['age_group'] = pd.cut(df['age'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

# Creating 'Season' feature
month_to_season = {
    'jan': 'Winter', 'feb': 'Winter', 'mar': 'Spring',
    'apr': 'Spring', 'may': 'Spring', 'jun': 'Summer',
    'jul': 'Summer', 'aug': 'Summer', 'sep': 'Autumn',
    'oct': 'Autumn', 'nov': 'Autumn', 'dec': 'Winter'
}
df['season'] = df['month'].map(month_to_season)

Handling Imbalanced dataset¶

EDA indicates that the target classes are in the ratio 88%:12%. This is an imbalanced dataset. A number of techniques are employed to address this issue.

Technique 1 - Random under sampling

Under sample the majority class by randomly picking samples with or without replacement

In [17]:
rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42, replacement=True)
x_rus, y_rus = rus.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

print('Original dataset shape:', Counter(y))
print('Resample dataset shape', Counter(y_rus))

Original dataset shape: Counter({0: 39922, 1: 5289})
Resample dataset shape Counter({0: 4198, 1: 4198})

Technique 3 - Under-Sampling: Tomek Links

Tomek links are pairs of very close instances but of opposite classes. Removing the instances of the majority class of each pair increases the space between the two classes, facilitating the classification process.

In [22]:
tl = RandomOverSampler(sampling_strategy='not minority')
x_tl, y_tl = tl.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
print('Original dataset shape', Counter(y))
print('Resample dataset shape', Counter(y_tl))

scores_lr_tl = cross_val_score(lr_model, x_tl, y_tl, scoring='f1', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
print("Cross Validation Score-TL:", scores_lr_tl.mean())
lr4 = lr_model.fit(x_tl, y_tl)
f1_lr_tl = f1_score(y_test, lr4.predict(X_test))
print("F1 score on test data:", f1_lr_tl)
results = pd.concat([results, pd.DataFrame([['LR-TomekLinks', scores_lr_tl.mean(), f1_lr_tl]], columns=results.columns)], ignore_index=True)

Technique 4 - SMOTE

This technique generates synthetic data for the minority class. SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) works by randomly picking a point from the minority class and computing the k-nearest neighbors for this point. The synthetic points are added between the chosen point and its neighbors.

In [23]:
smote = SMOTE()
x_smote, y_smote = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
print('Original dataset shape', Counter(y))
print('Resample dataset shape', Counter(y_smote))

scores_lr_smote = cross_val_score(lr_model, x_smote, y_smote, scoring='f1', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
print("Cross Validation Score-TL:", scores_lr_smote.mean())
lr5 = lr_model.fit(x_smote, y_smote)
f1_lr_smote = f1_score(y_test, lr5.predict(X_test))
print("F1 score on test data:", f1_lr_smote)
results = pd.concat([results, pd.DataFrame([['LR-SMOTE', scores_lr_smote.mean(), f1_lr_smote]], columns=results.columns)], ignore_index=True)

Technique 5 - NearMiss

NearMiss is an under-sampling technique. Instead of resampling the Minority class, using a distance will make the majority class equal to the minority class.

In [24]:
nm = NearMiss()
x_nm, y_nm = nm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
print('Original dataset shape', Counter(y))
print('Resample dataset shape', Counter(y_nm))

scores_lr_nm = cross_val_score(lr_model, x_nm, y_nm, scoring='f1', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
print("Cross Validation Score-TL:", scores_lr_nm.mean())
lr6 = lr_model.fit(x_nm, y_nm)
f1_lr_nm = f1_score(y_test, lr6.predict(X_test))
print("F1 score on test data:", f1_lr_nm)
results = pd.concat([results, pd.DataFrame([['LR-NearMiss', scores_lr_nm.mean(), f1_lr_nm]], columns=results.columns)], ignore_index=True)

Penalized SVM

During SVM training, we can use the argument class_weight=’balanced’ to penalize mistakes on the minority class by an amount proportional to how under-represented it is.

We also want to include the argument probability=True if we want to enable probability estimates for SVM algorithms.

In [25]:
psvm = SVC(class_weight='balanced', probability=True)
scores_psvm = cross_val_score(psvm, X_train, y_train, scoring='f1', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
print("Cross Validation Score-PSVM:", scores_psvm.mean())
psvm = psvm.fit(X_train, y_train)
f1_psvm = f1_score(y_test, psvm.predict(X_test))
print("F1 score on test data:", f1_psvm)
results = pd.concat([results, pd.DataFrame([['Penalized SVM', scores_psvm.mean(), f1_psvm]], columns=results.columns)], ignore_index=True)
